1. Start the Creation Process

    Log in to the Azure Portal.

    In the search bar at the top, type "Storage accounts" and select it.

    Click the + Create button.

2. Fill in the "Basics" Tab (Critical)

This is where most students get stuck due to region or naming rules.

    Subscription: Ensure "Azure for Students" is selected.

    Resource Group: Select the one you created earlier (or click "Create new").

    Storage account name: This must be unique across all of Azure, 3–24 characters, and lowercase letters/numbers only (no spaces or underscores).

        Example: mystudentwebsite2026

    Region: CRITICAL. Select one of the regions you found in your "Allowed Locations" list from the previous step. If you pick a random one like "East US" and it’s not allowed, the deployment will fail.

    Performance: Choose Standard (Recommended for students).

    Redundancy: Select Locally-redundant storage (LRS). This is the cheapest option and keeps your data in a single data center.

3. Review and Create

    You can skip the "Advanced," "Networking," and "Tags" tabs for a simple static site—the defaults are fine.

    Click Review + Create.

    Azure will run a "Validation." If it says "Validation Failed," click the red error message; it’s usually because the Region you picked isn't allowed by your student policy.

    If it says "Validation Passed," click Create.

4. Enable the "Static Website" Feature

Once the resource is created and says "Deployment is complete":

    Click Go to resource.

    On the left-hand menu, scroll down to the Data management section and click Static website.

    Set the toggle to Enabled.

    In the Index document name box, type index.html.

    Click Save.

5. Upload your files

    After saving, a link to a container named $web will appear. Click it.

    Click Upload and select your website files (HTML, CSS, JS) from your computer.

    Go back to the Static website tab. Your live site URL will be listed under Primary endpoint.


